# [AIPREF](../wg/aipref.html)

## Summary
The AIPREF meeting at IETF 119 served primarily as a status update and a context-setting session for the community. The Chairs provided an overview of the working group's progress, focusing on the refinement of core documents following previous objections during Working Group Last Call (WGLC). The group is currently focusing on a "Minimum Viable Product" (MVP) approach for its core drafts, specifically [draft-ietf-aipref-vocab](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-vocab/) and [draft-ietf-aipref-attach](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-attach/), by stripping out contentious terms to reach a baseline consensus before expanding scope.

## Key Discussion Points

### Working Group Status and Core Strategy
*   **Mark Nottingham** (Chair) noted that the group is focused on expressing preferences, not creating technical enforcement mechanisms. 
*   The group previously attempted a WGLC for [draft-ietf-aipref-vocab](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-vocab/) and [draft-ietf-aipref-attach](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-attach/), but objections led the chairs to pare back the scope. Contentious terms regarding "AI output" and "inference-time" preferences have been temporarily removed to refine the core semantics.
*   The goal is to establish a solid foundation and then evaluate new proposals for additional functionality.

### Refinement of Vocabulary and Search
*   **Mark Nottingham** discussed the evolution of the "search" carve-out. Originally intended to allow users to opt-out of AI training while remaining in search indexes, the discussion has become complex because modern search engines are increasingly built upon AI.
*   There is a shift in thinking from "AI control" to "presentation/display control"—how results are presented in chat interfaces versus traditional search rankings.
*   **Martin Thompson** (Editor) noted that while editors are cleaning up conformance text in the drafts, major progress on "meteor" issues (like search and inference) is stalled pending new proposals from the working group.

### Use Cases and Future Proposals
*   The Chairs have established a new Wiki page to collect use cases categorized by Training, Use, and Presentation.
*   **Suresh Krishnan** (Chair) and **Mark Nottingham** encouraged participants to focus on use cases specifically for the *expression* of preferences, consistent with the group's charter.
*   The group is looking for "purpose-based" or "display-based" preference proposals as a potential path forward beyond simple training signals.

### Intersection with Other Standards
*   **Benjamin Jimenez** raised a question regarding the scope of AIPREF in relation to broader user preference initiatives (e.g., IEEE standards for replacing cookie banners or general data usage preferences).
*   **Mark Nottingham** clarified that while the AIPREF vocabulary might be reusable in other contexts, the group must remain cautious of the "minefield" involving user agency, assistive technologies, and the balance of equities between content creators and tool users.

## Decisions and Action Items
*   **Action Item:** Working group participants are requested to submit use cases to the new Wiki page to help ground upcoming technical discussions.
*   **Action Item:** Any new proposals for the vocabulary or attachment mechanisms should be submitted to the mailing list substantially in advance of the April interim meeting to allow for proper evaluation.

## Next Steps
*   **Interim Meeting:** A multi-day interim meeting is scheduled for April in Toronto.
*   **Focus:** The Toronto interim will focus on honing the remaining training terms in the drafts and evaluating whether the group can reach consensus on broader preference types (purpose/display-based).
*   **Document Progression:** Editors will continue refining [draft-ietf-aipref-vocab](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-vocab/) and [draft-ietf-aipref-attach](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/draft-ietf-aipref-attach/) around the edges (conformance text) while waiting for the group to resolve substantive semantic issues.